Film scan day is an emotional day for me. 

I’m a deep feeling human and I won’t apologize for romanticizing absolutely everything. 

There is a place for me in this industry and I plan to be the only one who can take it. 

Bring me more of the avant-garde, the lucky in love, the fashion lovers, the Hollywood sadcore ballerina movie stars. 

I get you on a deep level. I’ve lived my whole entire life for this from my childhood Barbies playing wedding fashion show to my adulthood partying in the top floor at the Chateau Marmont. 

Stairwells and highways. 
Kisses I regret & still wish had lasted longer. 

A conflict, a push & pull, a contradiction. 

Submission to the moments of chaos that wedding days provide. 

Being overly poetic. Forgetting my first language in favor of looking through my lenses. Staying insane. Making dreams no longer seem strange, but everyday. 

And then I guess I should say something usual like I can’t wait to share more from this epic wedding.

xx Ashley

When selecting a film photographer it’s important to ask:

1. For how many years have you been shooting WEDDINGS on film?

2. How many rolls of film do you expect you’ll shoot at my wedding?

3. Are you able to shoot film with artificial lighting at the reception (not only disposables or Holga)? Do you have examples I can see from real weddings?

4. Can I see 3 galleries of real wedding work you shot as the lead photographer?

Why You Love Us:

🤍 Website & Instagram FULL of real wedding work all shot as lead photographer 

🤍 Can shoot medium format & 35mm film with both high end pro equipment & fun disposables & toy cameras at any time anywhere in any light with professional results (meaning in focus or intentionally blurred, detail remaining in highlights so your white dress isn’t a dress-shaped white space with no detail, etc)

🤍 We answer emails fast & texts even faster. You never have to wonder where you stand with our team or wait hours or days to find out something you need to know.

🤍 We know what we’re doing, so we work hella fast. No trial and error, yet we stay creative.

🤍 We shoot tons of film because we know how and we do it fast. Is it better than digital? For us it is because it is the tool we use to achieve our signature look. We do also shoot some digital, though & our 2nd & 3rd photographers always shoot digital. 

Hope that helps!

It’s me, hi. 🤍
And the AI version of me. 
Frequently Asked Questions:

Q: Can we have every single photo you take from our wedding?

A: No. I give you most of them, but not all. Some are accidental or are not flattering. I am a giver, though & provide nearly every photo I shoot. Not because I can’t cull, but because I know there’s nuance in expression & I want you to decide which photos you prefer & want to download. You know what you want better than me, I am the artist & you are yourself with your own internal feelings about your own expressions & appearance that no one else will ever understand & I respect that by giving you everything I think is within professional standards.

Q: Ashley, why are you always going to Ireland? Why do you know so much about Ireland? Why do you know Irish slang & have a cúpula focal? 

A: I taught myself Gaeilge at age 14. Why? I don’t know. I also learned Spanish and Japanese and some French. I love languages! Then I met & fell in love with this guy from Cork & he asked me to marry him & I said sure. My best friends are all from Ireland. My real estate agent is Irish (miss you Bernadette!), often I go weeks without hearing any accent other than Cork & Dublin. I guess the universe just decided that I need ALL the Irish people. I myself am simply American, but greatly influenced by my love of the whole entire world. My favorite place I’ve ever traveled is easily Cuba. But Ireland is our 2nd home and feels like home to me at this point more than my own hometown. 

Thanks for being here! Love you all.

Photographers who are learning always ask me how I get these kinds of shots on film.

If you didn’t know, it’s a technique called chiaroscuro. Beginners often want to call it “dark and moody,” “cinematic,” or “deep shadows.” It’s cinematic I suppose because it is a technique used in cinema, but it’s also used in painting and of course photography. Don’t ask me to pronounce it aloud, though. 

I have to go now and shoot a floral design workshop, but rest assured I will be back to explain the ins and outs and the whys and why nots of the chiaroscuro technique for weddings. 

It can be used to make an image jarring and creepy quite easily, particularly when we are putting faces in focus with partial light. We will want to avoid this, or use it so that it looks romantic and emotional, never startling in like a Halloween way.

The importance of the real.
🤍
Prospective clients, consider the value of real wedding work. I am always happy to send full galleries of real weddings. Editorials and styled shoots with professional models who pose themselves will tell you very little about a wedding photographer’s actual ability to pose non-pro models who perhaps are not even comfy in front of the camera. 

Over the weekend a beautiful workshop participant let me know that the way I interact with my clients and the way I hold myself while shooting made her feel so comfortable being photographed, which was not usual for her. This is so relatable for me. I’m uncomfortable being photographed and if a photographer comes at me with loud prompts or trying to hype me up I will withdraw into myself and the photos will be bad.

My approach to portraits is gentle, intuitive, calming. I will confidently guide you when necessary, giving quiet direction to capture the mood. 

The personality of the photographer can be seen in images and how we behave directly impacts the people being photographed. I never ever forget or take for granted how really sort-of brave it is to be in front of cameras all day. I do everything I can to make that painless for you. And if you are a pro model getting married and love posing yourself and being in front of the camera, fantastic. I’m here for you, as well. I love working with other creative people and feeling that artistic energy combine. So powerful.

Sufficient to say, if you’re hiring a wedding photographer to photograph your wedding, ask for their real wedding work. It’s not rude. What may seem like real weddings on websites is purely marketing and promotional shoots like when Arby’s takes a photo of a sandwich for their commercial and it’s made of styrofoam and paint and looks like a perfect representation of a sandwich. Then you go order one and it looks like a smashed leather shoe. Marketing is so much smoke and mirrors. I try to avoid this by having almost entirely real weddings on my feed and website, so. 

This is the best and funniest caption I’ve ever written and I am very proud and helpful. Sorry, Arby’s. You actually do a pretty good job.

This would’ve been easier to shoot on digital. Why do I shoot on real film even in complex situations?

For me it is about aesthetics. I prefer the look of real film. Some photographers will tell you that there is no “look of film” because it’s too variable, but in reality there absolutely is. Variation doesn’t negate the fundamental properties of an entire medium. 

Real film has a certain quality. At the end of the day, contemporary popular wedding photography looks overly smooth to me (has anyone else noticed this?) in a way I am not sure that I love. Maybe in time I’ll get used to it, but I have noticed a marked change in the images of photographers I once greatly admired. This is not a criticism to anyone and isn’t personal, it’s simply an artistic preference. I’m really trying to avoid viewing this type of content, as I think sometimes the human brain can confuse ubiquitous with good or desirable. I prefer to be overly analytical and ask myself what I really prefer. What my message is. What my standards are. And offer nothing less, even when it’s more expensive and not as easy.

I love doing my best to capture people being real and genuine. So many touching photos come from this approach. The only way to get here is experience with real weddings.

When hiring a photographer for your wedding, absolutely ask for real wedding work so you can be sure your photographer has the candid and other skills you will surely want captured.

Sometimes I feel it’s so unnecessary to explain what I love about art or which images in my wedding galleries meet that higher standard of “only Ashley could’ve taken this” or “yes this is art beyond traditional wedding photos.” However, I want to explain why this image meets that standard for me. 

When I saw this photo I fell in love. I’m not someone who believes all soft focus images are automatically artistically valuable. This one I will be printing, though and hanging in my office. It’s a treasure to me. The way Christina is wrapped in her veil by the wind and the sun. Her profile and the way the light hit her makes her hairstyle look almost completely different than it actually was, making her look almost Victorian or from another time. Her flowers could be spots of paint on a canvas. The hints of blue coming through against the yellow.

This was not staged or planned. I just saw it in the moment and took the photo, which is one of the best parts of my job. It’s always exciting when couples trust me and let me place them anywhere and understand that light and freedom and love are the most important factors in making art under a timeline on a once in a lifetime day.

You can’t see the whole photo here because of the instagram crop, and I know not everyone will get what I’m saying—some might even think “how pretentious.” And I don’t mind. It’s a huge universe and some of us were lucky enough to be born with a feeling for beauty, a beautiful sensitivity to emotion. So grateful people on that same wavelength tend to find me and hire me for their wedding photography. I pray to always, always, always have the strength and the impromptu creativity to make photos like this for my dear clients. 

It may sound flowery to some of you & that is okay. I genuinely love my clients & their families & badly want to always to them justice. I work so hard and am so committed to this. It’s so emotional for me. 🤍

When your ceremony is in mixed lighting, be sure your photographer is able to capture your dress details & skin, even if you are in direct sunlight. 

If your photographer is not skilled in metering, sunlight can create a situation where the human is so overexposed that there is no detail in the clothing or skin. It’s normal for colors to be brighter where the sun hits and there’s definitely more contrast, but having an image in which the skin or dress is purely white is a huge red flag in my opinion. In my image here, which I shot on Kodak film, it’s clear I shot the scene as it was in real life to preserve the colors and wedding clothes my clients so carefully chose. The shadows are darker, as shadows are.

For me, an image of lasting quality is one that isn’t overly stylized with filters and extreme brightness. I prefer my scenes to look as they were with normal colors and just a few drops of fairytale. 

I also love using 35mm and flash for guest shots. Really captures people’s personalities. As you can see, I am able to connect with people quickly, even though I am rather reserved & gentle. 
🥹🤍

I hope these tips help in your search for a wedding photographer!

Deceptively simple. So much goes into each photograph. While you may see a simple portrait of a beautiful bride, what you won’t see is the labor that went into creating this one image. 

The most important decision you can make (after who will be your wedding photographer) is who you will hire for hair and makeup. This is essential and will impact your satisfaction with your wedding images as well as your photographer’s ability to capture the best photos of your beautiful features. The success of your images lies in great part in the skill of your hair and makeup artist.

We want to avoid thick makeup that will crack. We want to avoid visible eyelash glue. We want to avoid over the top contouring, as when it becomes nighttime and your photographers need to bring out the flash, a non-professional contour job will look Halloweenish. If it isn’t blended to perfection, the flash will show the lines of demarcation and we don’t want that at all. 

I am very passionate about this topic because it so greatly impacts my work. 

@mua_reinakim is the beauty artist for this portrait and she is a genius. She made this look effortlessly chic. 🤍

It just looks better on TikTok since it’s a 3 minute video. But here is a little celebration of 2023. It’s time to start again and continue traveling the world for the love of love, film, friends, good times, & justice.

I’m leaving fear & pain in 2023 & moving forward into 2024 being my bravest self. I no longer want to be held back by worrying about things that might not happen, even though my life has been a series of the unthinkable actually happening. 

It’s been good, too though. I am so fortunate and so grateful. I pray to God I extend my privileges I was born with to those who don’t have them and continue to be a person who will run toward the burning building to bring back water for others once I’ve escaped. To continue to be unafraid to put myself between the oppressor and the oppressed so I can use my life for what’s right & good not just endlessly consuming & sharing content. 

I want to remember the forgotten, spend time with the lonely, and cherish the beauty of the planet.

We traveled the globe in 2023 for photography & will continue to do so in 2024. See you there, friends & lovers! If you’d like to work together I think that would be nice. 

With Love Always,

Ashley Johnny Cashley Noelle Edwards-Desmond, Professional Wedding Photographer & Scottie Dog Mother Extraordinaire 🥰

Artist notes: It’s funny how when you first begin to create art you forget yourself. You assume your own style & personal history is total boring crap & instead you choose to emulate those you admire.

Eventually, you put in years of hard work & oooh my my suddenly you’re good. The technical skills are more than solid. Now you can create anything you want. The work you once admired in others doesn’t thrill the way it used to. It’s easy to turn this into a crisis. Don’t do it, darling.

This is your call back to yourself. The echo of your own voice coming back to you from when you first set out to learn to create. It’s time now to be yourself. To make the art only you can make. You can make anything you want now! And what will you do? I’ll bet you money on it. You go back to being who you were all along. You make art that is similar to what you were into when you were 14. It’s your personal art inspired by your personal history. It’s your heart. You could’ve been making it all along. 

I swear if you skip the emulate others step you’ll be ahead by eons. 

I love who I am, the way my mind works, my competence, my creativity. I love connecting on a deep level with people. Intuition. Bravery. 

And why not hire an actual artist for your wedding photography? I think you should. 💌💋

Booking 2025. And might accept one more for 2024 if it aligns with my artistic goals &/or you love my work & no one else will do. Doesn’t have to be uber luxury style. I photograph weddings of all kinds. I’m not a snob whatsoever. I am expensive, but that’s because I know what I’m doing & nobody else is able to do it like I do. Being humble is a waste of time anyway, thanks for reading. Good talk.
